<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-02-16T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-02-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="71" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d71">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.00/1073.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-02-16">
                                    <hi rend="italic">February 16, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Yuan Shih-Kai unanimously elected President yesterday by the Nanking
                            assembly. To-day the Imperial family and the former Ministers of State
                            all urged him not to decline the office. The provisional capital is
                            fixed at Nanking. Sun telegraphs Yuan that an envoy has been sent to
                            invite him to come to Nanking.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Calhoun.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>